05769nam a22009135i 9780520973770DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192019cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2019023235  a97805209737707 a10.1525/97805209737702doi  a(DE-B1597)541509  a(OCoLC)1120695608  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aHV696.F6bD488 2020 4aHV696.F6 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a363.809747/12231 aDickinson, Maggie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFeeding the Crisis :bCare and Abandonment in America's Food Safety Net /cMaggie Dickinson. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCalifornia Studies in Food and Culture ;v7100tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Feeding the Crisis -- t2. Care and Abandonment in the Food Safety Net -- t3. The Carrot and the Stick -- t4. Men, Food Assistance, and Caring Labor -- t5. Free to Serve? Emergency Food and Volunteer Labor -- t6. No Free Lunch: The Limits of Food Assistance as a Public Health Intervention -- t7. Ending Hunger, Addressing the Crisis -- tPostscript: The Right to Food in the Trump Era -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program (SNAP), formerly known as food stamps, is one of the most controversial forms of social welfare in the United States. Although it's commonly believed that such federal programs have been cut back since the 1980s, Maggie Dickinson charts the dramatic expansion and reformulation of the food safety net in the twenty-first century. Today, receiving SNAP benefits is often tied to work requirements, which essentially subsidizes low-wage jobs. Excluded populations-such as the unemployed, informally employed workers, and undocumented immigrants-must rely on charity to survive.Feeding the Crisis tells the story of eight families as they navigate the terrain of an expanding network of assistance programs in which care and abandonment work hand in hand to make access to food uncertain for people on the social and economic margins. Amid calls at the federal level to expand work requirements for food assistance, Dickinson shows us how such ideas are bad policy that fail to adequately address hunger in America. Feeding the Crisis brings the voices of food-insecure families into national debates about welfare policy, offering fresh insights into how we can establish a right to food in the United States.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aFood reliefvCase studiesy21st century. 0aFood reliefxGovernment policyzUnited States. 0aFood reliefzNew York (State)zNew York. 0aFood securityzNew York (State)zNew York. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  abook about snap.  acontroversial form of social welfare.  aexcluded populations.  aexpansion and reformulation.  afood safety net.  afood stamps.  ainformally employed workers.  anational debates about welfare policy.  aright to food.  asnap benefits.  asnap.  astudy of comparative welfare reform.  asubsidizes low wage jobs.  asupplemental nutrition assistance program.  atells story of eight families.  atied to work requirements.  aundocumented immigrants.  aunemployed.  avoices of food insecure families.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Economics, Law & Social Sciences 2019 ENGz978311061013008iTitle is part of e